**Overall Cohesion Score: 8.5/10** — reads as one unified piece; every section earns its place.

### What's working (untouched)
- **Threaded payoffs.** The age-13 "I could die at any time" conviction is planted in §2, echoed in the Rabbit Hole, and lands the ending ("He had been saying versions of that since he was thirteen"). The word **"bit"** is deliberately carried from the close of Cowboy Tears ("Be seen without the bit") into the death section's second line ("assume it was a bit"). Nothing is orphaned.
- **Forward-pointing bridges** at §3→§4 ("watch what the gimmick was carrying") and §2→§3 ("Before the character, there was the music") are strong — the reader expects exactly what comes next.
- **Promise/delivery** is airtight: title's "meme so no one would see the artist underneath" is landed verbatim in the final paragraph.

### The one bump (minor)

**Transition §1 (diagnosis) → §2 (childhood) is the only weak seam.** Section 1 ends on "the talent underneath kept ambushing people who were certain there was nothing there," and Section 2 opens cold on a birth-year biography: "Oliver Tree Nickell was born in Santa Cruz in 1993…" The heading ("Raised Inside a Traveling Performance") does *some* thematic work, but there's no connective sentence, so the reader feels a small reset from psychology into biography.

**Proposed fix** — one bridging sentence at the top of §2, before the birth line, carrying the "manufactured self / frame" concept into the origin story:

> The instinct to build a frame and live inside it did not come from nowhere.

Then the existing "Oliver Tree Nickell was born in Santa Cruz in 1993…" follows. It's one short declarative line, matches the surrounding rhythm, no em-dash, no banned vocabulary, and doesn't steal the section's own "rolling stage" beat.

